            <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    The Church was very important to him, and his example was a great help to me, because I had not been raised in a home or a family that was active in the Church. My parents were not active when I was growing up, so when I finished my education and began looking for a companion of my own, I wanted someone with those qualities that Kenneth had. Our family became very strong in the Church. Our children have grown up loving the gospel. I attribute that to Kenneth's example and his determination to do what the Lord wanted him to do with his family. I've always admired Kenneth for that. He was not only faithful with himself, but he taught me as well. I've appreciated that so much in him.
            </span>
            
            <span id="SEE_MORE"><a href="#" id="restofstory1-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory1');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory1" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    Ken was always a very social person. That is, he loved to be around people. He would do almost anything to talk with someone else or to enjoy their company while he was working, traveling, or just talking and nothing else. When we were first married and he had farm work to do, he would beg, plead, cajole, connive, plan and do almost anything he could to talk me into going out into the field with him and just be with him as he did the farm work, drive the tractor, change the irrigation water, see to the livestock or most anything that needed to be done. And as our family grew and it became harder and harder for me to leave the house and go with him, it would please him very much to take one of the kids with him wherever he would have to go just to have company along, someone to visit with, no matter how small and of few words, just to have someone with him. <br /><br />

                    He was a very loving person to me. He was very kind, I don’t recall him ever raising his voice to me at all. I had free hand in taking care of the home. If something needed to be done, redecorating or something, I was always had free hand to make those choices, when we were financially able to do those things, he was always willing.<br /><br />

                    He was always affectionate. Whenever he would come in from the fields or work, or whenever he was going out, he would always come up to me and give me a kiss. It wasn’t just the first few years of marriage, it was throughout our entire marriage. In fact, one of my daughters told me one day, she said, “Mom, I know that my dad loves you because he was always coming up and kissing you.” So that became a very special thing. He was a very kind and quiet person with me, and generous with his time and abilities and finances. We did not want for very much; he was very kind in that way. 
                </span>

