            </span-->

            <span id="ChapterParagraphOne">
            <span id="BigFirstLetterText"></span>I do have one quite humorous incident that happened between Kenneth and I shortly after we were married. In fact, I think it was just that spring or early summer after we moved to the farm. I had been to Rigby to buy groceries, and I came home with three huge brown bags full of groceries—three of them—big bags full of groceries. 

<br />
            </span>

            <!--div id="ChapterPictureGallery" class="clearfix">
                <ol class="GalleryPics">
                    
                    
                </ol>    
            </div-->

            <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                Kenneth came in the kitchen while I was putting them away, and he said, “You spent $15 and that’s all you got?” I just looked at him and I could not believe what he said. So I reached in the sack and I pulled out a bag of beans, and I threw it at him. It broke and beans went all over the floor. He looked up at me and had that beautiful, big grin on his face and just walked out of the kitchen, not saying another word. And I had to clean up the beans. We laugh about that to this day.
            </span>
            <!--span id="SEE_MORE"><a href="#" id="restofstory2-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory2');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory2" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    Dr. West’s office consisted of his office room, a clinic room, two examination rooms, an x-ray room, and a lab room. I learned how to do x-rays while working there and also how to do many lab tests. It was very interesting work and I loved working there. Dr. West was a very fine man and a great family physician. It was nice to be working with Donna as she and I had been best friends since junior High school. We used to prepare our lunch in the lab room, and one of our favorite meals was to open a can of black bean soup, heat it up and relish it! I remember it was so delicious (whenever I pass the soup section of a supermarket and notice the cans of Campbell’s Black Bean Soup many long ago memories come creeping back to me).<br /><br />

                    One of the big fads those years was fur—to own a fur coat was really stylish! I almost gave in to purchase one but didn’t do it and was always glad that I hadn’t spent hard-earned money for foolish style. My friend Donna did buy a fur coat and lots of my friends as well.<br /><br />

                    During the winter of 1947 and 1948, I was busy with church activities and dating and went to dances and movies and church programs, etc. I dated a couple of fellows that winter-spring and have memories of lots of fun times. Dances were the great activities of the community and the church; tri-stake dances were held periodically as well as annual Gold and Green Balls. Movies were the great pastime and everyone went to at least a couple a week. Picnics on a date were also popular and swimming at Riverside or some of the local school pools. Wandermere was a great place for dancing, all to live bands playing the latest hits. 
 
                </span-->

