            <span id="textspanlichapter22">ALICE CHAU</span><br /><span id="textspanlichapter24">SISTER</span>
            </span-->

            <span id="ChapterParagraphOne">
            <span id="BigFirstLetterText"></span>Another positive thing about Kenneth was he never complained about my cooking, and I really didn’t know very much. When we moved to that farm, I didn’t know how to do anything. He never complained. He always ate what I put in front of him, and mostly would compliment me on the food. I appreciated that because it took me a long time to learn how to cook. I didn’t learn it in my mother’s home. I had to learn after we were married, and so Kenneth was very patient and kind with me that way. 
            </span>

            <!--div id="ChapterPictureGallery" class="clearfix">
                <ol class="GalleryPics">
                        
                </ol>    
            </div-->

            <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                He had two specialties that he prepared himself. He made wonderful tomato soup. He knew how to make it and it was excellent. Just a simple tomato soup. He also made wonderful scrambled eggs. He always told me exactly how to scramble the eggs. I don’t think, even to this day, that I scramble eggs and don’t think how he described to me what scrambled eggs should be like. He was very patient with me in learning how to cook. <br /><br />

                For the first batch of bread I made, my sister-in-law Flora May, who lived down the road from us, told me how to make it. So I tried to make some bread, and I didn’t put any yeast in it. It was definitely unleavened bread. That’s not our bread. Our bread has to raise up and be high, and that bread was not. It was flat as a rock. I think we laughed about that. I don’t think my feelings were hurt at all with that failure. Kenneth was very patient with me in that area as well.
            </span>
            <!--span id="SEE_MORE"><a href="#" id="restofstory3-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory3');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory3" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    As the Dark-Haired Nurse strolled down the aisles of the drugstore, named Walgreens, the Handsome Farmer, faint heart that he had, waited until she had left the drugstore and then, seeing a Friendly Face at the register, asked her if she could help him learn the identity of the Dark-Haired Nurse, lest his faint heart should perish with sadness as she walked out the door. The Friendly Face at the register said, “That Dark-Haired Nurse? Yes, I know her identity, she is Carma Ingram, the nurse who works in Dr. West's office just around the corner.” <br /><br />

                    How very happy was the heart of the Handsome Farmer! That very afternoon, his heart beating, “pitty-pat, pitty-pat,” he called the Dark-Haired Nurse and asked her for a date. Of course she said, “Of course, I've been waiting for you to call” (that's the way the Handsome Farmer told it). So that very evening, as the sun began to set on yonder hill, the Handsome Farmer drove his new green pickup (not cool back then!) to the home of the Dark-Haired Nurse, and found her waiting on the front lawn of her home, her heart beating, “pitty-pat, pitty-pat,” eagerly awaiting for the Handsome Farmer to arrive (that's how the Handsome Farmer told it). Actually the Dark-Haired Nurse was not able to enter the house because her Eager Father had placed the watering hose so the entry was blocked (that's how the Dark-Haired Nurse told it)! <br /><br />

                    And so the Handsome Farmer and the Dark-Haired Nurse at last met and their love story began. As the days and the weeks went by, their hearts became entwined in eternal love and the Handsome Farmer asked the father of the Dark-Haired Nurse for her hand. The father of course said, “Yes, take her away to the farm!” And so they were married and away they went to the farm and they promised forever to be true to each other for ever and ever (the words of the Handsome Farmer and the Dark-Haired Nurse)!
