            <span id="ChapterParagraphOne">
            <span id="BigFirstLetterText"></span>After Kenneth and I were married and we moved to the farm, I let my nursing career be at a standstill for a number of years. For about nine years I wasn’t working at all. <br /><br />
            
            Then I had the opportunity to go to work in the LDS hospital in Idaho Falls, and in that capacity I worked in the newborn nursery for several months. That was a choice experience for me. In those days the newborn nursery didn’t have a lot of special equipment to take care of premature babies. We didn’t have a special incubator to put them in at that time. We had oxygen for them, but they required a lot of nursing care, and it was required of them to be in the hospital for a long, long time. The nurses grew to love those little infants just like…I just can’t describe it to you. We became attached to those tiny little babies. 
            </span>

            <!--div id="ChapterPictureGallery" class="clearfix">
                <ol class="GalleryPics">
                        
                </ol>    
            </div-->

            <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                I remember two little premature babies that were born while I worked in that department at the hospital. One of them was a tiny little boy that was not much over two or three pounds. His last name was Hayes, and his parents were from Ririe. We took care of that little boy and grew to love him. When he was old enough and had gained enough weight that he could go home, we would cry. We had to let the babies go and we would cry. I know I did. I got attached to that little Hayes boy. 


            </span>
            <span id="SEE_MORE"><a href="#" id="restofstory5-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory5');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory5" class="more">
                <span id="ChapterParagraphTwo">
                    A long number of years later—well, it was nineteen years, was what it was!—I had been doing an errand for Kenneth up in Ririe, and I went into a feed store. I was in the office waiting to be taken care of, and this man walked over to me, tapped me on the shoulder, and said, “Are you Carma Bird?” I said yes. He asked, “You worked at the nursery in the Idaho Falls hospital?” I said, “Oh yes I did, a long time ago.” He said, “I want you to know, little boy Hayes is my son, and he’s just received a mission call. I recognized you, and I wanted you to know that the loving care that you gave to our son helped him to grow strong and healthy, to know that he was loved, and he’s now going to serve a mission.” <br /><br />

                    We had one other little premature baby, a little girl. Her parents were from St. Anthony, and I remember her name was Penny. She was a tiny little thing, just like the little Hayes boy. We grew to love those little babies because we had to give them such tender, careful care. I haven’t met the parents since then, but I have a special place in my heart for those tiny little babies and the special care they need, especially at that time when we didn’t have all the scientific help that we have now for little premature babies. <br /><br />

                    Those are two very special experiences while I was working employed as a nurse. <br /><br />

                    As I worked for the health department for twelve years, I had wonderful experiences because we were able to contribute things to the community: the clinics and the special things that we established in the county for the citizens. I worked in Madison County, and I had two school districts and a caseload of patients in the full county. <br /><br />

                    These were very special times for me in my nursing career. I enjoyed it a great deal. I loved being a nurse. It was a special blessing for me to be able to do that.
                </span>

